  "text": "Although the Bollen and Bartels PSSs had the poorest (0.61) and best discrimination (0.68) in this study, respectively, they were both essentially developed with a cohort of patients who received RT only. However, it is important for the patient sample to be representative of the intended population. The most recent external validation by Bartels et al [CITATION_1] supports this fact. They used the data from 58 patients who were treated with surgery followed by RT and from 52 patients who received RT only. They reported that both the overall performance (R 2 D , 0.02 vs 0.35) and the discrimination (c-statistic, 0.55 vs 0.75; D-statistic, 0.32 vs 1.5) were poorer for the surgical group versus the RT group. The fact that patients from the surgical group seemed fundamentally different from those in the RT group was further illustrated graphically: the estimated survival curve and the actual survival curve were very close for the radiation group, whereas they were quite far apart for the surgical group. In fact, similarly to our results, the Bartels model tended to underestimate survival in the surgical group.",
